<isis lang="en">
    <stitle>STARTING MOTORS - SOLENOID CHECKS - THREE TERMINAL SOLENOID</stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="check" graphiccount="2">
        <title>THREE TERMINAL SOLENOID</title>
        <para>As shown in
            <hotlnk xrefid="f0803617">Figure 17</hotlnk>, make connections to the "S" terminal and a clean metal ground.
            If needed, use the carbon pile to decrease battery voltage to the value specified in Specifications. Compare
            the ammeter reading with the hold-in winding specifications. A high reading indicates a defective winding
            (shorted or grounded hold-in, or a grounded pull-in), and a low reading indicates excessive resistance. To
            check the pull-in winding, connect from the solenoid switch terminal to the solenoid motor terminal (
            <hotlnk xrefid="f0803618">Figure 18</hotlnk>). Compare with the pull-in winding specification. A high
            reading indicates a shorted pull-in winding, and a low reading indicates excessive resistance.
        </para>
        <figure id="f0803617" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic id="g0803617" filename="../figg08/g0803617.webp" type="webp"/>
            <caption>Testing Solenoid Windings (Three-Terminal Solenoid)</caption>
            <calloutgroup>
                <callout1>1. VOLTMETER</callout1>
                <callout1>2. SWITCH</callout1>
                <callout1>3. AMMETER</callout1>
                <callout1>4. BATTERY</callout1>
                <callout1>5. CARBON PILE</callout1>
            </calloutgroup>
        </figure>
        <figure id="f0803618" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic id="g0803618" filename="../figg08/g0803618.webp" type="webp"/>
            <caption>Testing Solenoid Windings (Four Terminal Solenoid)</caption>
            <calloutgroup>
                <callout1>1. VOLTMETER</callout1>
                <callout1>2. SWITCH</callout1>
                <callout1>3. AMMETER</callout1>
                <callout1>4. BATTERY</callout1>
                <callout1>5. CARBON PILE</callout1>
            </calloutgroup>
        </figure>
        <specpara>
            <caution>
                <para>To avoid excessive heating, do not leave the pull-in winding connected for more than 10 seconds at
                    a time. The current will normally decrease as the heating increases.
                </para>
            </caution>
        </specpara>
    </svcproc>
